            <div type="commentary">
                 <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>The slab is also known as Rodney's Stone (Forsyth 1996, 139).</p>
                    </item>
                    <item n="2"><p>The fact that the Brodie Stone has been carefully dressed and all its carvings, apart from the ogham inscription, are in relatively high relief suggests a date later in the Pictish period (Forsyth 1996, 142).</p>
                    </item>
                    <item n="3"><p>Forsyth asserts that the raised bands on the slab were intended to bear the ogham and that all three inscriptions were part of the original design since the left-hand edge without ogham is only decorated with a narrower moulding similar to that outlining the cross (Forsyth 1996, 146).</p>
                    </item>
                    <item n="4"><p>The three inscriptions may be part of one continuous text, or represent independent units; either way, it is unclear in which order they should be read due to the poor condition of the carving (Forsyth 1996, 146). It is apparent though that all three oghams were carved in the same hand (Forsyth 1996, 155).</p>
                    </item>
                    <item n="5"><p>Due to the poor condition of the inscription, neither the language nor the full translation can be determined (Forsyth 1996, 156). Given the length of the inscripion combined with the fact that the typical 'MAQQ' does not seem to appear at any point, it is likely the original text incorporated more than proper nouns (ibid). Only one section, the EDDARRNONN on the back left representing the male personal name Etheman/ldamon, can be established with certainty (ibid). Though the name is Brittonic, the spelling could be Irish or Pictish (ibid).</p>
                    </item>                    
                    <item n="6"><p>The Brodie ogham is by far the longest ogham inscription from Scotland, originally consisting of up to seventy or eighty characters (Forsyth 1996, 157). Furthermore, <q>'it is noteworthy that, despite the length of the text, Brodie appears to lack both the x-forfid and the hammerhead A, the two most common forfeda in Scotland'</q> (Forsyth 1996, 156).</p>
                    </item>
                 </list>
            </div>
